<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Environment, Food and Rural Affairs Select Committee -</title></head><body><div><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:center; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Written evidence from the Local Government Association (WRT 002)</span></p></div><br style="clear:both; mso-break-type:section-break; page-break-before:auto" /><div><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">About the LGA</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Local Government Association (LGA) is the national voice </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of local government.  We work with councils to support, promote and improve local government.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We are a politically-led, cross party organisation which works on behalf of councils to ensure local government has a strong, credible voice with national govern</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ment.  We aim to influence and set the political agenda on the issues that matter to councils so they are able to deliver local solutions to national problems.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The LGA covers every part of England and Wales, supporting local government as the most efficie</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nt and accountable part of the public sector.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Overview</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Councils </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">across the country </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">play an essential role in keeping the public and businesses </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">moving </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">throughout the cold winter months.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Gritting roads, clearing snow, delivering meals on wheels, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">collecting prescriptions, are just some of the wide range of services councils provide for communities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and the national economy as a whole</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, during such challenging times. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Counci</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ls are well prepared for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> adverse winter weather. All stakeholders have lear</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ned significant lessons from the experiences of 2009/10, and the subsequent Quarmby review,</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> with greater preparations and response systems now in place t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">han prior to the 2009/10 winter. This includes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> better local coordination </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">across council boundaries and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> between local authorities, the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Highways Agency and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> D</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">epartment for Transport (DfT), as well as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">higher levels of salt stock to cope with extreme temperatures. </span></li></ol><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">However, c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ouncils want to do more but this is difficult in the face of further local </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">government cuts</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">totalling</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">43% over the spending review period until 2015/16.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> This will undoubtedly put pressure on the ability of local authorities to respond to significantly challenging winter weather. </span></li></ol><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Nonetheless, c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ouncils </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">continue to innovate locall</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">y and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">work </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">across council boundaries,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to make roads more resilient </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">through measures such</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> as</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> working with communities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, sharing information</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and investing in modern equipment</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to provide better resilience.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Councils are very well prepared for adverse winter weather.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Gritting roads, clearing snow and alerting communities and businesses are the essential services that keep the public and business going throughout the cold winter months</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In 2010 the Government asked David Quarmby CBE to undertake a review of winter resilience, which produced an interim report in July 2010 and a final report in October.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> In the wake of this report, councils have worked hard to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ensure they would be prepared f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">or a winter of similar proportions to that experienced in 2009/10.</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">When it comes to gritting those parts of the network for which councils are responsible, p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">riority is given to those with the heaviest traffic flow, major bus routes, and links to hospitals</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, fire stations, police stations and large schools. Roads linking villages, smaller schools and places like GPs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> surgeries are also prioritised.</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Department for Transport (DfT) carries out regular audits of council stock levels during the gritting seas</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">on and every year the LGA conducts a survey of councils’ preparations for winter. The results of this autumn’s surveys are not yet available but we understand from DfT that local highway authorities are in a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">strong position, with salt orders underway and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">eliveries</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> from suppliers taking place</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  </span></li></ol><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The LGA would be happy to share a copy of this autumn’s research findings with the Select Committee once compiled.</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Initial estimates suggest that local authorities expect to hold a similar level of salt as last </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">year (approximately 1.2 million tonnes) as we enter the winter season – nearly twice the 700,000 tonnes used in the 2011-12 winter and about the same amount as was used in the severe winter of 2010-11. LGA’s Winter Readiness Survey 2012/13 (108 responses f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rom 174 councils, 62%) found that 20</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> per cent</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of councils had more salt than they had the previous year and 69</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> per cent had </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the same.  </span></li></ol><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As councils use salt during the gritting season</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> they order replace</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ment stocks from the suppliers who, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">we understand</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> fr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">om the DfT,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> have significant reserves. In addition</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> DfT keeps a strategic stockpile for use as a last resort</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, which l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ast year was </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">approximately</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">425,000 tonnes. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">DfT has issued a Strategic Salt Protocol Note </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to councils </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">which sets out the arrangement</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s for allocation of strategic salt, if and when required, including the price of salt.</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Since the last severe winters, the LGA</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> has</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">continued to work cl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">osely with the DfT and other key partners in the run-up to winter. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">For instance, the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">LGA has set up an online </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">forum</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> dedicated to winter weather preparedness, through which participants can share their experiences, best practice and policy developments.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There are also liaison arrangements between LGA, the DfT and the Highways Agency to enab</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">le the communication of concerns and working together in the event of severe winter weather. The LGA is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> also</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> included in Cabinet Office resilience arrangements in relation to winter weather.</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Winter weather poses a number of challenges to highways authorit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ies.  It is important to remember that salt doesn’t work in conditions colder than minus 10C, although in such rare conditions councils would continue to plough roads where it was possible to do so safely. In addition</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> rain can wash away salt leaving roads</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> prone to re-icing. Councils </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">also </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sometimes have to contend with ‘freezing rain’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> supercooled rain which falls when the surface temperature is below zero, freez</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> on impact</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">which means they may need to re-grit areas.</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">15</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> per cent</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of councils responding t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">o last year’s winter weather survey reported </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">salt being stolen</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, some suffering losses of 20 tonnes, mainly from grit bins. On occasions this is the result of nearby residents </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">collecting</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">it for their </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">gardens and patios, or it is stockpiled by nearby </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">businesses</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, while </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">there have</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> also</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> been reports of people selling it door-to-door.</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Despite such challenges, councils are arguably more prepared now than ever before. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Councils are continuing to innovate and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">work in partnership to make</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> roads more resilient</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Councils are continuing to innovate and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">work in partnership to make roads more</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> resilient through measures such</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> as</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> working with communities, sharing information and investing in modern equipment to provide better resilience.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ouncils have invested in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">modern equipment to address th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e challenges of winter weather. For example, the findings of the LGA’s 2012 survey highlighted significant investment in new gritters, improved snow </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ploughs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> blades</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, footway gritters, tractors, snow-blowers and quad bikes.  </span></li></ol><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Examples of technological innovation and improvement include:</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 68.05pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">18.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A new type of gritting technique</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> spreading dry salt and salt mixed with brine trialled last winter by Cheshire </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">East</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Council</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. The solution is less easily removed by passing vehicles or strong w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">inds and lasts longer without retreatment. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 68.05pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 68.05pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">18.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Last winter West Sussex County Council deployed a brand new fleet of 26 gritters which use 20 per cent less salt, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">are equipped with a GPS system called ‘Coldsnap</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’ which makes it possible to monitor gritting</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> throughout the county on a minute by minute basis. It also used an electronic monitoring system so that more salt could be ordered if required.</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 68.05pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 68.05pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">18.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Brighton &amp; Hove City Council acquired a fleet of new gritting wagons</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> which have better fuel economy, are less</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> polluting, and use a more effective spreader</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. The council also invested in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a new sit-on ‘Unimog’ vehicle for clearing pavements, which will be better for hilly and narrow streets. </span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 68.05pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 68.05pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">18.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Hampshire County Council trialled some innovative ‘back to black’ snow pl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ough blades last year which remove more snow by ploughing closer to the road surface. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">For </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">roads outside the gritter network</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> councils are working with local communities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to minimise the impact of severe weather</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. For example, this includes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> supplying local </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">grit bins for residents, liaising with parish councils and community groups to grit more residential or remote areas and working with farmers to clear rural areas, in line with the recommendations of the Quarmby report. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">For example, l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ast winter, v</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">oluntary Snow Wardens</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in areas </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">which are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">out of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> reach of gritters</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> were supported by Bristol City Council to apply salt</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> clear icy areas and arrange basic checks on elderly or vulnerable neighbours.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Elsewhere,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Surrey County Council enlisted 50 farmers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> with ploughs to clear snow across the county</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, whilst i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n Essex</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> 180 parish and town councils signed up for the county counci</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">l’s new winter salt bag scheme where p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">articipating </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">local </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">councils received one tonne of salt for use on very localised and problemat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ic areas of the highway. </span></li></ol><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Councils are also </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">providing critical information to their residents through a variety of means – including social media</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. The 2012 LGA survey identified that 78</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> per cent</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of councils would be providing live updates to residents on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">weather, gritting activity and services. 98</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> per cent</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of these </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">had</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a dedicated resource on their website</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> 76</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> per cent </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">us</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a Twitter feed and 33</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> per cent</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a Facebook page. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Case studies of specific </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">examples of good practice</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> from last winter</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> includ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 69.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">21.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Stockton-on-Tees Borough Council published a leaflet sent to thousands of residents, as part of its regular magazine, about winter and council services, including how to clear pavements, drive in snow and the locations of its 300 grit bins. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 69.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 69.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">21.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Authorities u</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sing a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Gritter Twitter</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> account included West Sussex County, Sandwell Council Gloucestershire County Council and Solihull Council. This allow</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ed the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> councils to tell people when roads </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">were </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">being treated, give weather updates and winter driving advice.</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 69.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">21.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Mor</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e than 13,500 residents signed up to Northumberland County Council’s alerts system which use</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> its website, social media like Twitter and Facebook, and smartphone apps to pass on the latest information on weather, school closures, road conditions/closures, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">flood alerts, bin collections and emergencies.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Conclusion</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">terms of reference for this inquiry ask</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> whether </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">more should be done to ensure a coordinated response. The LGA believes that all stakeholders have learned significant lessons from the experiences of 2009/10 and the subsequent Quarmby review with more robust preparation and response systems in place</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> evidence shows that c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">uncils have improved salt stock levels</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and gritting practices, purchased new technology and equipment and done more to work with communities and parish councils in response to severe weather.</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Local authorities consult tirelessly wit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">h interested parties in their area, including their local communities, about their preparations for managing the network during severe weather conditions. Each authority tailors this to best suit their unique area, using a combination of direct engagement </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and other methods of communication such as online tools.</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Councils would like to do more and will seek to make continuing improvements in coordination, information sharing and reducing theft, however, this is difficult in the face of further local governme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nt cuts (totalling 43% over the spend</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ing review period until 2015/16</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">). </span></li></ol><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Furthermore, the damage done to the road network by recent severe weather </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">has</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> contributed to the significant backlog of road maintenance </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">facing local </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">councils. Without more funding </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">this cannot be eliminated.</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">October 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-indent:18pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> See </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20111014014059/http:/transportwinterresilience.indepe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">ndent.gov.uk/</span></p></body></html>